ght\"|3,000||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.43\n|style=\"text-align:right\"|8,192||style=\"text-align:right\"|792||style=\"text-align:right\"|23,760\n|colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"|352\u00d7576, 704\u00d7288\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|L5\n|style=\"text-align:right\"|1,792||style=\"text-align:right\"|8,000||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.22\n|style=\"text-align:right\"|16,384||style=\"text-align:right\"|1,620||style=\"text-align:right\"|48,600\n|colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"|720\u00d7576\n|-style=\"background:#EEF;font-size:smaller\"\n!scope=\"row\" colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right\"|Units\n|scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\"|kbits\n|scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\"|kbits/s\n|scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\"|seconds\n|scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\"|bits\n|scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\"|macroblocks\n|scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\"|macroblocks/s\n|scope=\"col\" colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"|pixels\n|}\n\nMore advanced profiles for HD media have been defined later in the AVC profile, which is functionally identical to the ITU H.264 standard but are now also integrated in MPEG-4 Part 10 (see [[H.264/MPEG-4 AVC#Levels|H.264/MPEG-4 AVC]] for the list of defined levels in this AVC profile).\n\n==Licensing==\n{{See|MPEG-4 Part 2#Patent holders}}\n\nMPEG-4 contains patented technologies, the use of which requires licensing in countries that acknowledge [[software patent|software algorithm patents]]. Over two dozen companies claim to have patents covering MPEG-4. [[MPEG LA]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mpegla.com/main/programs/M4V/Pages/Intro.aspx |title=MPEG Licensing Authority\u00a0\u2013 MPEG-4 Visual: Introduction |access-date=2011-01-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626135353/http://www.mpegla.com/main/programs/M4V/Pages/Intro.aspx |archive-date=2018-06-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> licenses patents required for MPEG-4 Part 2 Visual from a wide range of companies (audio is licensed separately) and lists all of its licensors and licensees on the site. New licenses for MPEG-4 System patents are under development<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mpegla.com/main/programs/M4S/Pages/Intro.aspx |title=MPEG Licensing Authority\u00a0\u2013 MPEG-4 Systems: Introduction |access-date=2011-01-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122184315/http://www.mpegla.com/main/programs/M4S/Pages/Intro.aspx |archive-date=2011-01-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and no new licenses are being offered while holders of its old MPEG-4 Systems license are still covered under the terms of that license for the patents listed ([https://web.archive.org/web/20101121025049/http://www.mpegla.com/main/programs/M4S/Pages/PatentList.aspx MPEG LA&nbsp;\u2013 Patent List]).\n\nThe majority of patents used for the MPEG-4 Visual format are held by three Japanese companies: [[Mitsubishi Electric]] (255 patents), [[Hitachi]] (206 patents), and [[Panasonic]] (200 patents).<ref name=\"mpegla\">{{cite web |title=MPEG-4 Visual - Patent List |url=https://www.mpegla.com/wp-content/uploads/m4v-att1.pdf |website=[[MPEG LA]] |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[MPEG]]\n* [[MPEG-4 Structured Audio]]\n* [[MPEG-4 SLS]]\n* [[ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 29]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://mpeg.chiariglione.org/standards/mpeg-4/mpeg-4.htm Overview of the MPEG-4 Standard] at the MPEG Official Website\n* {{webarchive |url=https://archive.is/20121022022747/http://www.m4if.org/mpeg4/ |title=MPEG Industry Forum (MPEGIF) MPEG-4 page |date=2012-10-22}}\n* {{webarchive |url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20100108135001/http://www.m4if.org/public/documents/vault/MPEG4WhitePaperV2a.zip |title=MPEG Industry Forum (MPEGIF) MPEG-4 White Paper |date=2010-01-08}}\n* [http://iphome.hhi.de/suehring/tml/ JM MPEG-4 AVC /H.264 Reference Code]\n* [http://sourceforge.net/projects/openipmp/ OpenIPMP: Open Source DRM Project for MPEG-4]\n{{Compression formats}}\n{{ISO standards}}\n{{MPEG}}\n{{List of International Electrotechnical Commission standards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mpeg-4}}\n[[Category:Audio codecs]]\n[[Category:ISO/IEC standards]]\n[[Category:MPEG-4]]\n[[Category:Video codecs]]\n[[Category:Videotelephony]]\n", "name_user": "Mykoshurtech", "label": "safe", "comment": "I changed a dead link to my blog post.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MPEG-4"}
{"title_page": "Mudyl River", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n  | name              = Mudyl River\n  | image             = \n  | image_size        = \n  | image_alt         =\n  | image_caption     = \n  | map               = \n  | map_size          = \n  | map_alt           =\n  | map_caption       = \n  | source1_location  = \n  | mouth_location    = [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]]\n  | subdivision_type1 = Country\n  | subdivision_name1 = [[Russia]]\n  | progression       = {{RKolva}}\n  | length            = {{convert|33|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n  | source1_elevation = \n  | mouth_elevation   = \n  | discharge1_avg    = \n  | basin_size        = \n  | river_system      = \n  | tributaries_left  =\n  | tributaries_right =\n}}\n'''Mudyl''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0443\u0434\u044b\u043b\u044c}}) is a river in [[Perm Krai]], [[Russia]], a [[:wikt:left bank|left]] tributary of the [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]], which in turn is a tributary of the [[Vishera River (Perm Krai)|Vishera River]]. The river is {{convert|33|km|mi}} long. It flows into the Kolva River {{convert|20|km|mi}} from Kolva's mouth.<ref name='\u041c\u041f\u0420 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438'>{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=180409|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0420\u0424: \u041c\u0443\u0434\u044b\u043b\u044c}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Perm Krai}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Russia}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Perm Krai]]\n\n\n{{PermKrai-geo-stub}}\n{{Russia-river-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n  | name              = Mudyl River\n  | image             = \n  | image_size        = \n  | image_alt         =\n  | image_caption     = \n  | map               = \n  | map_size          = \n  | map_alt           =\n  | map_caption       = \n  | source1_location  = \n  | mouth_location    = [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]]\n  | subdivision_type1 = Country\n  | subdivision_name1 = [[Russia]]\n  | progression       = \n  | length            = {{convert|33|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n  | source1_elevation = \n  | mouth_elevation   = \n  | discharge1_avg    = \n  | basin_size        = \n  | river_system      = \n  | tributaries_left  =\n  | tributaries_right =\n}}\n'''Mudyl''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0443\u0434\u044b\u043b\u044c}}) is a river in [[Perm Krai]], [[Russia]], a [[:wikt:left bank|left]] tributary of the [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]], which in turn is a tributary of the [[Vishera River (Perm Krai)|Vishera River]]. The river is {{convert|33|km|mi}} long. It flows into the Kolva River {{convert|20|km|mi}} from Kolva's mouth.<ref name='\u041c\u041f\u0420 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438'>{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=180409|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0420\u0424: \u041c\u0443\u0434\u044b\u043b\u044c}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Perm Krai}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Russia}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Perm Krai]]\n\n\n{{PermKrai-geo-stub}}\n{{Russia-river-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "progression", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mudyl_River"}
{"title_page": "John Register", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = John Register\n| image         = \n| alt           =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = John Sherman Register<ref name=\"NYT01\">{{cite web\n |title        = Paid Notice: Deaths  BARRETT, DOROTHY PRATT\n |newspaper    = New York Times\n |author       = \n |date         = February 12, 1998\n |url          = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/12/classified/paid-notice-deaths-barrett-dorothy-pratt.html}}</ref> \n| birth_date    = February 1, 1939<ref name=\"swart\"/>\n| birth_place   = [[New York]], US\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1996|4|9|1939|2|1}}\n| death_place   = [[Malibu]], [[California]], US\n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| movement      = [[Realism]]\n| training      = \n| field         = Painting\n| works         = \n}}\n'''John Register''' (1939\u20131996) was an American realist artist, noted for his spare paintings and drawings, which were most often minimalist depictions of hotels, caf\u00e9s, and empty chairs.<ref name=\"swart\"/><ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> \n\n==Background==\nRegister was born in 1939<ref name=\"swart\"/> in New York City to Dorothy Deming Pratt Register (1909-1998) and Samuel Croft Register.<ref name=\"NYT01\"/> His parents divorced when he was three, and his father died when he was eleven.<ref name=\"swart\"/> His maternal great-grandfather, [[Charles Pratt]] was one of [[John D. Rockefeller]]'s partners in the formation of the [[Standard Oil Company]] (now Exxon), as well as founder of [[Charles Pratt and Company]] in New York and [[Pratt Institute]] in Brooklyn. \n\nRegister graduated from the [[Lawrenceville School]] in New Jersey. After graduating from the University of California, Berkeley, with B.A. in Literature in 1961, he met his wife Catherine Richards in a photography class at  [[ArtCenter College of Design|Pasadena Art Center]] where he studied commercial art. Register also studied painting for a semester at the [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] in Paris,<ref name=\"swart\"/> and later studied at the [[California School of Fine Arts]] in San Francisco.  \n\nIn 1964 the two moved to New York, where Register studied design and television at the [[Pratt Institute]] (founded by his great-grandfather).<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> They married on February 6, 1964<ref name=\"wedding\">{{cite web\n |title        = MIss Richards, John S. Register Planning to Wed\n |publisher    = New York Times\n |author       = \n |date         = December 21, 1963\n |url          = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1963/12/21/89996221.html?pageNumber=13}}</ref> and together had three children. During this period Register pursued a successful career as an advertising art director at Young & Rubicam and later McCaffrey and McCall &mdash; and lived in a Fifth Avenue apartment.<ref name=\"swart\"/>  \n\nIn 1972, just after his 33rd birthday, and unhappy with his work,<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> Register excused himself from an important client meeting saying he had a dental appointment, wrote a note to his boss and never returned.  He subsequently became a full-time painter, spent a year in New York painting every day, and studied briefly at the [[Art Students League]]<ref name=\"league\">{{cite web\n |title        = John Register: A Retrospective\n |publisher    = Frederick R. Weisman Museum of Art\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.tfaoi.com/aa/1aa/1aa88.htm}}</ref> &mdash; before moving with his family to California. His interests included racing cars and ice-boats, photography, tennis, running, competitive chess, letter writing, reading, backpacking, fishing, and surfing.<ref name=\"swart\">{{cite web\n |title        = John Register\n |publisher    = SWart\n |author       = \n |date         = February 1, 2000\n |url          = https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/OBITUARY-John-Register-2986924.php}}</ref> \n\nRegister was born with a serious genetic kidney disease <ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> and suffered kidney failure 15 years before his death. He received a kidney transplant from his sister in 1981 and, when that failed, received another transplant in 1985. In September 1994, he was told he had four to six weeks to live. He lived instead for 18 months, battling cancer (caused by [[Immunosuppressive drug|anti-rejection medication]])<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> until his death in 1996 at the age of 57, in Malibu, California.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\">{{cite web\n |title        = OBITUARY -- John Register\n |publisher    = SFGate\n |author       = Carl Nolte\n |date         = April 11, 1996\n |url          = https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/OBITUARY-John-Register-2986924.php}}</ref><ref name=\"examiner\">{{cite web\n |title        = OBITUARY -- John Sherman Register\n |publisher    = San Francisco Examiner, p. 12\n |author       = \n |date         = April 13, 1996\n |url          = https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/461614481/}}</ref> \n\nAt the time, Register was survived by his wife, Catherine R. Register, <ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite web\n |title        = John Sherman Register; Painter of L.A. Cityscapes \n |publisher    = LA Times\n |author       = Myrna Oliver\n |date         = April 13, 1996\n |url          = https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-04-13-mn-58051-story.html}}</ref> (Catherine R. Murff); his mother, Dorothy Pratt Register Barrett (1909-1998) (then remarried) of Hillsborough, California; his sister, Barbara Pratt Register of Rolling Hills, California; his brother, Eliot Steven Barrett (1943-2013) of St. Helena, California; and his three children, Peter Eliot Register, David Croft Register and Kathryn (Kate) Sisson Register; and a grandson, John Sherman Register II.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>\n\n==Work==\nRegister said \"I look for offbeat beauty. I don't know what I'm looking for until I find it. There are things so ugly that I can't paint them. Sometimes I get depressed by that city, and by other cities I visit. But I like the patina of things that have been battered by life\".\n\nIn his 1989 biography of Register, ''John Register Persistent Observer, Barnaby Conrad, wrote that Register's \"vision of isolated streets, empty coffee shops, long shadows, old hotels, and bus stations represent a haunting stillness tinged with regret and hope.\"<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/>\n\nRegister studied with the portrait painter Raymond Kinstler and landscape painter [[Lennart Anderson]].<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> He had his first show in Los Angeles in 1975 and received the Francis J. Greenburger Foundation Award from the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Museum]].<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> \n\nHe has shown at the Modernism Gallery in San Francisco, David Stuart Gallery in Los Angeles, the Earl McGrath Gallery in Santa Monica, and the [[Laguna Art Museum]].<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/> With his work often compared to [[Edward Hopper]]'s,<ref name=\"hopper\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Haunting Realism of John Register\n |publisher    = LA Modern Auction\n |author       = \n |date         = May 15, 2016\n |url          = https://lamodern.com/2016/05/the-haunting-realism-of-john-register/}}</ref><ref name=\"league\"/>a show of drawings by Mr. Register and [[Edward Hopper]] took place in 1996. The [[San Jose Museum of Art]] hosted a major retrospective show of Mr. Register's work in the fall of 1997.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> The exhibit ''John Register: Persistent Observer'' took place at the [[Frederick R. Weisman Museum of Art]] at Pepperdine University, Malibu, CA, in 2000, subsequently traveling to his alma mater, the [[Lawrenceville School]], Lawrenceville, NJ, and later to the West Valley Art Museum, [[Sun City, Arizona]].<ref name=\"swart\"/>\n \nRegister's work was used, and credited, as the inspiration for the video for \"[[Turn My Head]]\" by the band [[Live (band)|Live]] in 1997. His paintings were also featured in the movie ''[[In Her Shoes (2005 film)|In Her Shoes]]'', (2005), the director, [[Curtis Hanson]] using the paintings to suggest \"loneliness.\"<ref name=\"ridley\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ridley Scott Encyclopedia\n |publisher    = Scarecrow Press, 2009, p. 156\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://books.google.it/books?id=xBGFacfGR0gC&pg=PA156&lpg=PA156&dq=john+register+%22in+her+shoes%22+curtis+hanson&source=bl&ots=82U7nipDXD&sig=ACfU3U1qq_mCxC2k4KLp0KAQvZhh-Fn2yg&hl=it&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiZrZmQ3ezoAhUVBhAIHYETClUQ6AEwC3oECA4QLw#v=onepage&q=john%20register%20%22in%20her%20shoes%22%20curtis%20hanson&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* [[Barnaby Conrad III|Conrad, Barnaby III]]. ''John Register: Persistent Observer.'' Duane Press, 1999.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.modernisminc.com/artists/John_REGISTER/ Register at Modernism.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928175116/http://www.sjmusart.org/content/collection/highlights/paintings/item_info.phtml?itemID=24&typeID=paintings ''Desert Landscape'' at the San Jose Museum of Art.]\n*[http://artregister.com/SeavestIntroductiontoCollection/Catalogue/RegisterConversation.html ''The Conversation'' at the Seavest Collection.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Register, John}}\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:American realist painters]]\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:Precisionism]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Painters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Kidney transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawrenceville School alumni]]\n[[Category:Advertising people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = John Register\n| image         = \n| alt           =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = John Sherman Register<ref name=\"NYT01\">{{cite web\n |title        = Paid Notice: Deaths  BARRETT, DOROTHY PRATT\n |newspaper    = New York Times\n |author       = \n |date         = February 12, 1998\n |url          = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/12/classified/paid-notice-deaths-barrett-dorothy-pratt.html}}</ref> \n| birth_date    = February 1, 1939<ref name=\"swart\"/>\n| birth_place   = [[New York]], US\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1996|4|9|1939|2|1}}\n| death_place   = [[Malibu]], [[California]], US\n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| movement      = [[Realism]]\n| training      = \n| field         = Painting\n| works         = \n}}\n'''John Register''' (1939\u20131996) was an American realist artist, noted for his spare paintings and drawings, which were most often minimalist depictions of hotels, caf\u00e9s, and empty chairs.<ref name=\"swart\"/><ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> \n\n==Background==\nRegister was born in 1939<ref name=\"swart\"/> in New York City to Dorothy Deming Pratt Register (1909-1998) and Samuel Croft Register.<ref name=\"NYT01\"/> His parents divorced when he was three, and his father died when he was eleven.<ref name=\"swart\"/> His maternal great-grandfather, [[Charles Pratt]] was one of [[John D. Rockefeller]]'s partners in the formation of the [[Standard Oil Company]] (now Exxon), as well as founder of [[Charles Pratt and Company]] in New York and [[Pratt Institute]] in Brooklyn. \n\nRegister graduated from the [[Lawrenceville School]] in New Jersey. After graduating from the University of California, Berkeley, with B.A. in Literature in 1961, he met his wife Catherine Richards in a photography class at  [[ArtCenter College of Design|Pasadena Art Center]] where he studied commercial art. Register also studied painting for a semester at the [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] in Paris,<ref name=\"swart\"/> and later studied at the [[California School of Fine Arts]] in San Francisco.  \n\nIn 1964 the two moved to New York, where Register studied design and television at the [[Pratt Institute]] (founded by his great-grandfather).<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> They married on February 6, 1964 and together had three children. During this period Register pursued a successful career as an advertising art director at Young & Rubicam and later McCaffrey and McCall &mdash; and lived in a Fifth Avenue apartment.<ref name=\"swart\"/>  \n\nIn 1972, just after his 33rd birthday, and unhappy with his work,<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> Register excused himself from an important client meeting saying he had a dental appointment, wrote a note to his boss and never returned.  He subsequently became a full-time painter, spent a year in New York painting every day, and studied briefly at the [[Art Students League]]<ref name=\"league\">{{cite web\n |title        = John Register: A Retrospective\n |publisher    = Frederick R. Weisman Museum of Art\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.tfaoi.com/aa/1aa/1aa88.htm}}</ref> &mdash; before moving with his family to California. His interests included racing cars and ice-boats, photography, tennis, running, competitive chess, letter writing, reading, backpacking, fishing, and surfing.<ref name=\"swart\">{{cite web\n |title        = John Register\n |publisher    = SWart\n |author       = \n |date         = February 1, 2000\n |url          = https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/OBITUARY-John-Register-2986924.php}}</ref> \n\nRegister was born with a serious genetic kidney disease <ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> and suffered kidney failure 15 years before his death. He received a kidney transplant from his sister in 1981 and, when that failed, received another transplant in 1985. In September 1994, he was told he had four to six weeks to live. He lived instead for 18 months, battling cancer (caused by [[Immunosuppressive drug|anti-rejection medication]])<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> until his death in 1996 at the age of 57, in Malibu, California.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\">{{cite web\n |title        = OBITUARY -- John Register\n |publisher    = SFGate\n |author       = Carl Nolte\n |date         = April 11, 1996\n |url          = https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/OBITUARY-John-Register-2986924.php}}</ref><ref name=\"examiner\">{{cite web\n |title        = OBITUARY -- John Sherman Register\n |publisher    = San Francisco Examiner, p. 12\n |author       = \n |date         = April 13, 1996\n |url          = https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/461614481/}}</ref> \n\nAt the time, Register was survived by his wife, Catherine R. Register, <ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite web\n |title        = John Sherman Register; Painter of L.A. Cityscapes \n |publisher    = LA Times\n |author       = Myrna Oliver\n |date         = April 13, 1996\n |url          = https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-04-13-mn-58051-story.html}}</ref> (Catherine R. Murff); his mother, Dorothy Pratt Register Barrett (1909-1998) (then remarried) of Hillsborough, California; his sister, Barbara Pratt Register of Rolling Hills, California; his brother, Eliot Steven Barrett (1943-2013) of St. Helena, California; and his three children, Peter Eliot Register, David Croft Register and Kathryn (Kate) Sisson Register; and a grandson, John Sherman Register II.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>\n\n==Work==\nRegister said \"I look for offbeat beauty. I don't know what I'm looking for until I find it. There are things so ugly that I can't paint them. Sometimes I get depressed by that city, and by other cities I visit. But I like the patina of things that have been battered by life\".\n\nIn his 1989 biography of Register, ''John Register Persistent Observer, Barnaby Conrad, wrote that Register's \"vision of isolated streets, empty coffee shops, long shadows, old hotels, and bus stations represent a haunting stillness tinged with regret and hope.\"<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/>\n\nRegister studied with the portrait painter Raymond Kinstler and landscape painter [[Lennart Anderson]].<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> He had his first show in Los Angeles in 1975 and received the Francis J. Greenburger Foundation Award from the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Museum]].<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> \n\nHe has shown at the Modernism Gallery in San Francisco, David Stuart Gallery in Los Angeles, the Earl McGrath Gallery in Santa Monica, and the [[Laguna Art Museum]].<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/> With his work often compared to [[Edward Hopper]]'s,<ref name=\"hopper\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Haunting Realism of John Register\n |publisher    = LA Modern Auction\n |author       = \n |date         = May 15, 2016\n |url          = https://lamodern.com/2016/05/the-haunting-realism-of-john-register/}}</ref><ref name=\"league\"/>a show of drawings by Mr. Register and [[Edward Hopper]] took place in 1996. The [[San Jose Museum of Art]] hosted a major retrospective show of Mr. Register's work in the fall of 1997.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> The exhibit ''John Register: Persistent Observer'' took place at the [[Frederick R. Weisman Museum of Art]] at Pepperdine University, Malibu, CA, in 2000, subsequently traveling to his alma mater, the [[Lawrenceville School]], Lawrenceville, NJ, and later to the West Valley Art Museum, [[Sun City, Arizona]].<ref name=\"swart\"/>\n \nRegister's work was used, and credited, as the inspiration for the video for \"[[Turn My Head]]\" by the band [[Live (band)|Live]] in 1997. His paintings were also featured in the movie ''[[In Her Shoes (2005 film)|In Her Shoes]]'', (2005), the director, [[Curtis Hanson]] using the paintings to suggest \"loneliness.\"<ref name=\"ridley\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ridley Scott Encyclopedia\n |publisher    = Scarecrow Press, 2009, p. 156\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://books.google.it/books?id=xBGFacfGR0gC&pg=PA156&lpg=PA156&dq=john+register+%22in+her+shoes%22+curtis+hanson&source=bl&ots=82U7nipDXD&sig=ACfU3U1qq_mCxC2k4KLp0KAQvZhh-Fn2yg&hl=it&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiZrZmQ3ezoAhUVBhAIHYETClUQ6AEwC3oECA4QLw#v=onepage&q=john%20register%20%22in%20her%20shoes%22%20curtis%20hanson&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* [[Barnaby Conrad III|Conrad, Barnaby III]]. ''John Register: Persistent Observer.'' Duane Press, 1999.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.modernisminc.com/artists/John_REGISTER/ Register at Modernism.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928175116/http://www.sjmusart.org/content/collection/highlights/paintings/item_info.phtml?itemID=24&typeID=paintings ''Desert Landscape'' at the San Jose Museum of Art.]\n*[http://artregister.com/SeavestIntroductiontoCollection/Catalogue/RegisterConversation.html ''The Conversation'' at the Seavest Collection.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Register, John}}\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:American realist painters]]\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:Precisionism]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Painters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Kidney transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawrenceville School alumni]]\n[[Category:Advertising people]]\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Register"}
{"title_page": "Rudolph Leibel", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = Rudolph Leibel\n| image       = Rudolph Leibel, MD.jpg\n| caption     = Rudolph Leibel, 2012\n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1942}}\n| birth_place = [[United States of America]]\n| spouse      = Lulu Leibel \n| residence   = United States\n| citizenship = [[United States]] \n| ethnicity  = Jewish\n| fields    = [[Molecular Genetics]], [[Obesity]], [[Diabetes Mellitus]], [[Pediatrics]]\n| workplaces = [[Boston Children's Hospital]], [[Cambridge Hospital]], [[Massachusetts General Hospital]], [[Rockefeller University]], [[Columbia University]]\n| alma_mater = [[Colgate University]], [[Albert Einstein College of Medicine]]\n| known_for = Co-Discovery of [[Leptin]], Advancing the Understanding of [[Obesity]]\n| editorial boards = [[Journal of Clinical Investigation]], [[International Journal of Obesity]]\n| influences        = Jules Hirsch, [[Douglas L. Coleman]]\n| awards = [[National Academy of Sciences]] [[Institute of Medicine]] Member; TOPS Scientific Achievement Award; NIH/HHS Intragency Committee on Human Nutrition Research; New York State Science, Technology and Academic Research (NYSTAR) Distinguished Professor; Albert Einstein College of Medicine Distinguished Alumnus Award; Berthold Medal of the European Society of Endocrinology, Federation Award for Biomedical Research of the Federation of Medical Scientific Societies of the Netherlands, Leiden University; [[National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases]] Federal Advisory Council Member; The Christopher J. Murphy Professorship of Diabetes Research at [[Columbia University]]; Honoris Causa Doctorate, [[Louisiana State University]] \n}}\n\n'''Rudolph Leibel''' (born 1942) is the Christopher J. Murphy Professor of Diabetes Research, Professor of Pediatrics and Medicine at [[Columbia University Medical Center]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.columbiadoctors.org/prof/rlleibel |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419014352/http://www.columbiadoctors.org/prof/rlleibel |archivedate=2014-04-19 }}</ref> and Director of the Division of [[Molecular Genetics]] in the Department of Pediatrics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cumc.columbia.edu/pediatrics/division/molecular-genetics/faculty|title=Faculty - Department of Pediatrics - Columbia University College of Physicians & Surgeons|website=www.cumc.columbia.edu}}</ref> He is also Co-Director of the Naomi Berrie Diabetes Center<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nbdc.cumc.columbia.edu/our-research-faculty#0 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419023808/http://nbdc.cumc.columbia.edu/our-research-faculty#0 |archive-date=2014-04-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and Executive Director of the Russell and Angelica Berrie Program in Cellular Therapy,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.russellberriefoundation.org/initiative_dmi_cellulartherapy.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419025317/http://www.russellberriefoundation.org/initiative_dmi_cellulartherapy.php |archive-date=2014-04-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Co-Director of the New York Obesity Research Center<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110824105803/http://www.nyorc.org/co-director.aspx]</ref> and the [[Columbia University]] Diabetes and Endocrinology Research Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://derc.cumc.columbia.edu/|title=Diabetes Research Center|website=Diabetes Research Center}}</ref>\n\nLeibel's co-discovery at [[Rockefeller University]] of the [[hormone]] [[leptin]], and cloning of the [[leptin]] and [[leptin receptor]] genes, has had a major role in the area of understanding [[human]] [[obesity]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{ cite book |author = Shell E | title = The Hungry Gene: The Inside Story of the Obesity Industry | publisher = Atlantic Monthly Press | date = January 1, 2002 | chapter =Chapter 4: On the Cutting Edge | isbn = 978-1422352434 }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{ cite book |author = Shell E | title = The Hungry Gene: The Inside Story of the Obesity Industry | publisher = Atlantic Monthly Press | date = January 1, 2002 | chapter =Chapter 5: Hunger |  isbn = 978-1422352434 }}</ref> Leibel has published hundreds of scientific papers on obesity, and has authored and co-authored 70 scientific papers on the topic of leptin specifically.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 23070544 | doi=10.1210/en.2012-1510 | volume=153 | title=TNF-\u03b1 up-regulates protein level and cell surface expression of the leptin receptor by stimulating its export via a PKC-dependent mechanism | pmc=3512064 | year=2012 | journal=Endocrinology | pages=5821\u201333  | last1 = Gan | first1 = L | last2 = Guo | first2 = K | last3 = Cremona | first3 = ML | last4 = McGraw | first4 = TE | last5 = Leibel | first5 = RL | last6 = Zhang | first6 = Y}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 22761182 | doi=10.1152/ajpregu.00092.2012 | volume=303 | title=Effects of ambient temperature on adaptive thermogenesis during maintenance of reduced body weight in mice | pmc=3423991 | year=2012 | journal=Am J Physiol Regul Integr Comp Physiol | pages=R438-48  | last1 = Ravussin | first1 = Y | last2 = LeDuc | first2 = CA | last3 = Watanabe | first3 = K | last4 = Leibel | first4 = RL}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 21593810 | doi=10.1038/oby.2011.111 | volume=20 | title=Responses of gut microbiota to diet composition and weight loss in lean and obese mice | pmc=3871199 | year=2012 | journal=Obesity (Silver Spring) | pages=738\u201347  | last1 = Ravussin | first1 = Y | last2 = Koren | first2 = O | last3 = Spor | first3 = A | last4 = LeDuc | first4 = C | last5 = Gutman | first5 = R | last6 = Stombaugh | first6 = J | last7 = Knight | first7 = R | last8 = Ley | first8 = RE | last9 = Leibel | first9 = RL}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 22326217 | doi=10.1016/j.cmet.2012.01.002 | volume=15 | title=Challenges and oppor